# Copy to .env.local and fill in. .env.local is gitignored.

# Control-plane Postgres (D7: same engine backs the Workflow World).
DATABASE_URL=postgres://eden:eden@localhost:5442/eden

# Runtime mode: 'oss' (default, local/BYO impls) or 'managed' (KMS/gateway/Stripe).
EDEN_MODE=oss

# Local secrets encryption key (AES-256-GCM). 32 bytes as 64 hex chars.
# Generate with: openssl rand -hex 32
EDEN_SECRETS_KEY=

# Better Auth — email/password authentication with the organization plugin.
# Generate at least 32 bytes of high-entropy secret material: openssl rand -base64 32
BETTER_AUTH_SECRET=
# Public same-origin URL where Eden is served (no trailing slash).
BETTER_AUTH_URL=http://localhost:5173

# Transactional email for password resets and workspace invitations.
# Production uses Postmark. FROM_EMAIL must be a verified Postmark sender.
POSTMARK_SERVER_TOKEN=
FROM_EMAIL=Eden <noreply@example.com>
# Optional development-only SMTP transport (for Mailpit/Mailtrap). It takes precedence locally.
# Credentials embedded in this URL must be URL-encoded.
SMTP_URL=

# GitHub App (Connect pillar). Register an App with repo Contents R/W, Pull requests,
# and set its Setup URL to http://localhost:5173/connect. Then fill these in.
# GITHUB_APP_ID=
# GITHUB_APP_SLUG=eden-your-app        # from the App's public URL github.com/apps/<slug>
# GITHUB_APP_CLIENT_ID=
# GITHUB_APP_CLIENT_SECRET=
# GITHUB_APP_PRIVATE_KEY=              # PEM; single line with \n escapes, or a real multiline value
# GITHUB_WEBHOOK_SECRET=               # optional until we wire webhooks (M1)

# Discord app (optional — one-click Discord channel, issue #32). Register ONE Discord app for
# this Eden installation in the Developer Portal (discord.com/developers/applications) and add
# <origin>/discord/callback to its OAuth2 Redirects. Then fill these in; users connect servers
# from the Deployment tab. The Interactions Endpoint URL is set automatically at connect time.
# EDEN_DISCORD_APPLICATION_ID=         # Application ID (General Information)
# EDEN_DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN=              # Bot token (Bot tab) — stays on the control plane, never shipped to instances
# EDEN_DISCORD_PUBLIC_KEY=             # Public Key (General Information) — Ed25519, hex

# Google OAuth client (optional — install-time auth-brokered connections, issue #30). Register ONE
# OAuth 2.0 Client (Web application) for this Eden installation in Google Cloud Console and add
# <origin>/google/callback to its Authorized redirect URIs. Then fill these in; users connect
# Google (e.g. for the Google Sheets connector) from the install wizard / Deployment tab. See
# catalog/templates/connections/google-sheets for the publishing-status ladder (verification and
# refresh-token-expiry implications of Internal vs Testing vs Production).
# EDEN_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=               # OAuth 2.0 Client ID
# EDEN_GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=           # OAuth 2.0 Client secret — stays on the control plane
#
# Additional OAuth providers (issue #163) follow the same pattern: register an OAuth app with
# the provider, set EDEN_<PREFIX>_CLIENT_ID / EDEN_<PREFIX>_CLIENT_SECRET (the <PREFIX> is the
# provider's envPrefix in app/connections/providers.server.ts), and register the canonical
# redirect URI <origin>/connections/<provider>/callback. Google alone keeps the legacy
# <origin>/google/callback.
#
# Exceptions (issue #167): a PUBLIC-client provider (tokenEndpointAuth "none") has no secret —
# only EDEN_<PREFIX>_CLIENT_ID is needed. A provider with dynamic client registration (mayi)
# needs NO client env at all: Eden registers one OAuth client per grant at Connect time; the
# only operator requirement is a publicly reachable EDEN_PUBLIC_ORIGIN (below), because the
# provider validates every registered callback URL as public HTTPS.

# Public origin of this Eden control plane (e.g. https://eden.example.com). When set, every
# deployed instance receives EVE_PUBLIC_ORIGIN=<origin>/e/<environmentId> — its public ingress
# URL — so channels/connections that take inbound webhooks can build callback URLs.
# EDEN_PUBLIC_ORIGIN=

# Model access. Uses OpenRouter unless an org key is set in Settings.
# OPENROUTER_API_KEY=
# EDEN_ASSISTANT_MODEL=anthropic/claude-sonnet-5

# Deploy target: container | local-docker | nomad | vercel
EDEN_DEPLOY_TARGET=local-docker
EDEN_INSTANCE_PORT=3000

# Background job worker (builds/deploys run here, not in request handlers)
# EDEN_WORKER_POLL_MS=2000
# EDEN_DISABLE_WORKER=1               # e.g. in one-off scripts/tests

# Traffic splitter (weighted, session-sticky ingress across live Releases)
# EDEN_SPLITTER_PORT=8787
# EDEN_DISABLE_SPLITTER=1

# Legacy Eve model strings can still call Vercel AI Gateway directly. Eden-authored model
# choices use OpenRouter wiring instead.
# AI_GATEWAY_API_KEY=
# VERCEL_OIDC_TOKEN=
